%N A390249 Numbers k that are the hypotenuse of at least one primitive Pythagorean triangle whose perimeter + inradius and perimeter - inradius are both prime.
%C A390249 Numbers of the form m^2 + n^2 where 1 <= n < m, m and n are coprime with one odd and one even, and 2*m^2 + m*n + n^2 and 2*m^2 + 3*m*n - n^2 are prime.
%H A390249 Robert Israel, <a href="/A390249/b390249.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%e A390249 a(3) = 25 is a term because 25 is the hypotenuse of the primitive Pythagorean triangle with sides 24, 7, 25 having perimeter 24 + 7 + 25 = 56 and inradius (24 + 7 - 25)/2 = 3 and both 56 - 3 = 53 and 56 + 3 = 59 are prime.
%e A390249 a(14) = 265 is the first term that corresponds to more than one primitive Pythagorean triangle: sides (23, 264, 265) and (247, 96, 265).
%p A390249 N:= 10000: # for terms <= N
%p A390249 R:= NULL:
%p A390249 for m from 1 while m^2 < N do
%p A390249   for n from 1 + (m mod 2) to m by 2 while m^2 + n^2 <= N do
%p A390249     if igcd(m,n) > 1 then next fi;
%p A390249     if isprime(2*m^2 + m*n + n^2) and isprime(2*m^2 + 3*m*n - n^2) then
%p A390249   R:= R, m^2+n^2;
%p A390249 fi od od:
%p A390249 sort(convert({R},list));
